Both partim and alii refer to quibusdam. Such anacolutha, where only one of a pair of words such as alter-alter, alius-alius etc. is expressed and the other replaced, in another sentence, by some other expression, are very common in Cic. Madvig has collected a large number of examples in the first excursus toliis De Finibus. — fugiendas ete: Cic. is here evidently imitating a chorus of the Hip- polytus of Euripides 253 etseq.
